---
/**
 * storage-engines · storage-engines-fundamentals · Figure 5 — Level 5, the
 * leftmost-prefix rule on a composite index (account_id, created_at) + covering.
 *
 * Copied VERBATIM from the source page (figure + svg + figcaption incl. the
 * footnote <sup>). This figure references no markers, so it needs no local
 * <defs>.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 560 160"
        role="img"
        aria-label="Leftmost-prefix rule on a composite index (account_id, created_at)"
    >
        <g font-family="ui-sans-serif,system-ui,sans-serif">
            <text
                x="280"
                y="18"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="11.5"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#1f3a5a"
                >composite index (account_id, created_at) — sorted lexicographically</text
            >
            <g font-size="9.5">
                <rect x="20" y="34" width="250" height="28" rx="6" fill="#eef5ee" stroke="#2f5d3a"
                ></rect><text x="30" y="52" fill="#244a2e"
                    >WHERE account_id=42 AND created_at&gt;X ✓ full use</text
                >
                <rect x="20" y="68" width="250" height="28" rx="6" fill="#eef5ee" stroke="#2f5d3a"
                ></rect><text x="30" y="86" fill="#244a2e"
                    >WHERE account_id=42 ✓ leading prefix</text
                >
                <rect x="20" y="102" width="250" height="28" rx="6" fill="#f7ecea" stroke="#9a2417"
                ></rect><text x="30" y="120" fill="#7a2218"
                    >WHERE created_at&gt;X ✗ no left-anchored prefix</text
                >
            </g>
            <rect x="300" y="40" width="246" height="88" rx="8" fill="#fbfaf2" stroke="#7a1f12"
            ></rect>
            <text
                x="423"
                y="60"
                text-anchor="middle"
                font-size="10.5"
                font-weight="700"
                fill="#7a1f12">covering index = no row fetch</text
            >
            <text x="423" y="80" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" fill="#6b675f"
                >index holds every column the query reads</text
            >
            <text x="423" y="96" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" fill="#6b675f"
                >→ Postgres "Index Only Scan"</text
            >
            <text x="423" y="116" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9.5" fill="#9a2417"
                >cost: wider index, fewer rows/page, slower writes</text
            >
        </g>
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        Put the equality column first, the range column second — a range on the leading column "uses
        up" the sort order and forces a scan.<sup><a href="#s2" id="r2b">2</a></sup>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
